<div id="review_1259403061" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1259403061" />
    <a title="Laurie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26553024-laurie"><img alt="Laurie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1623871223p2/26553024.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1259403061?book_show_action=true">Apr 19, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laurie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laurie" href="/user/show/26553024-laurie">Laurie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26553024-laurie?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26553024-laurie?shelf=north-africa">north-africa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26553024-laurie?shelf=history-of-ideas">history-of-ideas</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26553024-laurie?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26553024-laurie?shelf=colonialism">colonialism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26553024-laurie?shelf=social-justice-racism">social-justice-racism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1259403061" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10391339438469685228">Dr. Franz Fanon wrote The Wretched of the Earth in 1961; it was the same year that he died, it was the same year that I was born. And while there is nothing significant in the last fact to anyone beyond myself, I find myself chagrined to note that I&apos;ve been on this earth 55 years without previously encountering Fanon&apos;s work. <br/><br/>The Wretched of the Earth is an important book. It was in 1961 and I believe it remains so in 2016. Fanon&apos;s analysis of the necessity for violence as the primary means to tr</span>
  <span id="freeText10391339438469685228" style="display:none">Dr. Franz Fanon wrote The Wretched of the Earth in 1961; it was the same year that he died, it was the same year that I was born. And while there is nothing significant in the last fact to anyone beyond myself, I find myself chagrined to note that I've been on this earth 55 years without previously encountering Fanon's work. <br /><br />The Wretched of the Earth is an important book. It was in 1961 and I believe it remains so in 2016. Fanon's analysis of the necessity for violence as the primary means to truly liberate colonized people (specifically Black-Arab Africans of Algeria) culturally, economically, nationally and psychologically will challenge the thinking of many living in an era which experienced Dr. King Jr.'s non-violent civil rights movement. Reading with an open mind to the parallels between colonial Algeria and the U.S. in the present day one can more easily understand the context spontaneous #BlackLivesMatter movement. <br /><br />Dr. Fanon is indeed a physician; a psychiatrist. His chapter on the colonial war and its relationship to mental disorders in both the colonized and colonizing peoples, complete with case studies is a fascinating look at how living under a colonizing, despotic regime is indeed crazy-making. Yet in 1961, Dr. Fanon expresses cautious hope that the nations of the African continent will reject the European model and lifestyle; will create its own way of thinking, its own unique humanity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10391339438469685228" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


